Σε περίπτωση που έχεις μια πιστότατη δεξιότητα στο χρησιμοποιήσεις μέσω JavaScript, θα είναι αρκετά εύκολο να γράψεις έναν αριθμόπακτό μόνο αυτοκόκκινος σύνδρομο (Sinon) από αυτό το JavaScript, ώστε να αποδείξεις αυτήν:

```js
// Sinon.js
function sinon() {
    const arr = [].concat(); // Create the array with one item
    const name = arr[0];
    return {
        name: name,
        get(prop) {
            // Return the name of the array at prop (0,1,2...)
            return name;
        }
    };
}
```
Την υπόθεση, είσαι JavaScript-friendly, θα υπάρχει JavaScript-friendly αρχικός JavaScript. Plain JS is not necessary here as we are talking about a single item. I am assuming you are familiar with `const` and `let` syntax. If not, I can explain. I have replaced `var` with `const` and `let` so that variables are initialized once and only once. I have also added a default parameter to `sinon()` so that you can use it with just one argument or many arguments. It returns a function called `Sinon`. The function has a property called `name` which is the same as the first argument of `sinon()`. We can get a value of the property using `.get()` which is an alias of `.property()` and passes a name of the property to be accessed. If we would like to get something from the object itself we can use `.get(0)` or just `.get()`. This will return us the array containing one item.

